El Miércoles, 22 de octubre, 2014 22:24:35, "ﾛﾌﾞｿﾝｺﾞｰﾄﾞﾝ robsongo@... [nihontostudy]" <nihontostudy@yahoogroups.com> escribió:


 
Hi,

Actually, the signature reads Tango no Kami Kanemichi. This is the second generation. I am sorry to hear that the blade has been badly damaged as the signature is very close to being genuine.

Gordon Robson

2014-10-23 7:12 GMT+09:00 Eduardo Fontenla eduardofontenla@... [nihontostudy] <nihontostudy@yahoogroups.com>:
 
Dear T
Thank you very much!
Unfortunately the blade is very, very damaged 
Not worth even trying a polished, has the mark of generations of children have played with that sword...
There came to my hands with the tsuba, one seppa, a habaki and the blade destroyed.
Any other information that you could add? 
Then I will upload photos of what remains of that blade
Thanks and regards from Argentina


El Miércoles, 22 de octubre, 2014 18:57:38, "junkmail@... [nihontostudy]" <nihontostudy@yahoogroups.com> escribió:


 
Eduardo -
    The inscription reads "Tamba no Kami Yoshimichi" and it looks to be a well cut mei. Not to say that it is genuine, we really would have to see some photos of the blade but first impression looks pretty good.
-t
